Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"nl":{"1503–":"1503–Overleden","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1500–Male":"1500–Overleden","1515–1584":"1515–1584","1530–Male":"1530–Overleden","1503–Female":"1503–Overleden","1571":"1571","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","about 1530":"circa 1530","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Standon, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Standon, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1503–":"1503–Deceased","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1515–1584":"1515–1584","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1503–Female":"1503–Deceased","1571":"1571","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","about 1530":"about 1530","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Standon, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Standon, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crawford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: habitational name from any of various places called Crawford, primarily the one in Lanarkshire (Scotland), and possibly also from the one in Lancashire. Both are named in Old English with <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Crafford","meanings":["English (Cumberland) and Scottish: variant of   Crawford  ."]},{"name":"Crofoot","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Crawford  .","English: variant of<b>Crowfoot</b>, a nickname for someone with splayed feet or someother deformity of the foot, from Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ +<i>fōt</i> ‘foot’. In Middle English <i>crou-fot</i> also denotedthe buttercup, and it may be from this sense that the name arose,although the reason for its adoption is unclear."]},{"name":"Crofut","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Crawford   or <b>Crowfoot</b> (see   Crofoot  )."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":46,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":55,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":66,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":68,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":97,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":117,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Joan Crawford was born in 1503, in England. She married Nicholas Shipley in 1520, in England."},"et":{"1503–":"1503–Surnud","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1515–1584":"1515–1584","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1503–Female":"1503–Surnud","1571":"1571","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","about 1530":"umbes 1530","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Standon, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Standon, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1503–":"1503–Kuollut","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1515–1584":"1515–1584","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1503–Female":"1503–Kuollut","1571":"1571","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","about 1530":"noin 1530","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Standon, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Standon, Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"1503–":"1503–Décédée","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1515–1584":"1515–1584","1530–Male":"1530–Décédé","1503–Female":"1503–Décédée","1571":"1571","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1584":"158